#Text=Fit Wind Deflectors
#Text=Wind deflectors allow you to open your car window during a stormy day without getting rain on your upholstery .
#Text=They can also reduce the noise made when you roll your window down by deflecting the wind away from your window .
#Text=Because wind deflectors are easy to install , fitting them to your car does not require a trip to the mechanic or any special tools .
#Text=As long as you clean the channels beforehand and insert the deflectors carefully , they should fit comfortably in your window frame .
#Text=Steps
#Text=Preparing the Window Frame and Deflectors
#Text=Buy wind deflectors made for your car model .
#Text=Wind deflectors are specially designed for different car models .
#Text=Make sure that the wind deflectors you buy are suitable for your car .
#Text=If you purchase the wrong kind , you will not be able to achieve a perfect fit .
#Text=You can find the car model information on the wind deflector 's packaging .
#Text=If you 're not sure what kind to buy , ask a salesperson for advice .
#Text=Roll your window down .
#Text=To fit the wind deflector in , you will need to roll your window at least halfway down .
#Text=If your window does not roll down to the bottom , you can still fit your deflector in but may not be able to clean your window as thoroughly .
#Text=Clean the window frame and channel .
#Text=Spray a window cleaner or mild solvent over the tops and sides of the window and wipe it off with a paper towel or dry cloth .
#Text=Rub off any dirt , dust , or debris in the window frame so your wind deflector will fit in securely .
#Text=If you are installing an adhesive wind deflector , clean off the window 's trim ( the painted door frame to the top and sides of the window ) as well with the cleaner and dry cloth .
#Text=Use a damp cloth or screwdriver to scrape dirt away from the bottom of the frame .
#Text=Pull your cloth through the slot and pick out any large pieces of debris that might be stuck in the slot .
#Text=If you cannot pull out the debris using the cloth , pick it out with a screwdriver instead .
#Text=Let the window frame dry before fitting in the deflector .
#Text=If you install the deflector while the window frame is still wet , your deflector may not attach as tightly .
#Text=Give the windows time to air dry or wipe the frame and slot down with a dry towel before you prepare your wind deflector .
#Text=Inserting In-Channel Deflectors
#Text=Place the wind deflector into the top window channel .
#Text=Lift the deflector into the top corners of the channel first and push it into place .
#Text=Press up on the middle and sides of the wind deflector to keep it securely fitted into the frame .
#Text=Attach any window clips , if applicable .
#Text=Some wind deflectors come with clips to adhere the wind deflector 's edges in place .
#Text=If your wind deflector comes with any clips , push them up between the deflector and the window to fasten it in place .
#Text=Your wind deflector 's instructions should indicate where , specifically , to put the clips in .
#Text=Check the window for obstructions .
#Text=After you have put the deflector in place , roll the window up to check that it still works properly .
#Text=If your window cannot roll up , try adjusting the wind deflector to shift it out of the way .
#Text=This is especially important for electric windows , which may refuse to roll up if they sense an obstruction in the way .
#Text=If you adjust the wind deflector , be careful not to force it in any position , as you may accidentally damage it .
#Text=Keep your window rolled up for 24 hours .
#Text=Roll the window back up after you 've finished adjusting its alignment and let it sit for at least 24 hours .
#Text=This will give the wind deflector enough time to mold into the window so it will stay in place .
#Text=Use a maintenance spray on the window if it works slowly .
#Text=If your wind deflector seems to slow your windows down , use maintenance spray around the window channels and slot to keep it from catching on the frame while rolling up or down .
#Text=You can purchase maintenance spray online or at most auto shops .
#Text=Applying Adhesive Deflectors Instead
#Text=Peel off a small section of the double-sided tape liner from both sides .
#Text=Several inches or centimeters is enough to test the deflector 's fit .
#Text=Place the wind deflector along the top of the window trim to test its approximate fit .
#Text=Do not remove all of the double-sided tape until you 've aligned the wind deflector .
#Text=Adjust the wind deflector 's alignment .
#Text=Line the wind deflector up with the top of the window trim as closely as possible .
#Text=When you 've achieved an even fit , apply pressure to the peeled ends of the adhesive to secure the wind deflector in place .
#Text=If the wind deflector does not align with the top of the window , it may be the wrong size .
#Text=Remove the remainder of the adhesive tape .
#Text=Pull on the adhesive tape 's end strips until you have entirely removed them from the wind deflector .
#Text=Apply pressure to the wind deflector as you peel off the tape to stick it firmly on your car .
#Text=Test the wind deflector for adherence .
#Text=After you 've bonded the wind deflector to your car , try to wiggle the deflector up and down .
#Text=If the deflector has adhered properly , it should n't move .
#Text=Apply more pressure to loose areas or adjust the wind deflector 's positioning if it does move .
#Text=Tips
#Text=Wear gloves while cleaning your car and handling the wind deflectors to avoid smudging either as you work .
#Text=Things You 'll Need
#Text=Paper towel
#Text=Microfiber cloth
#Text=Maintenance spray
#Text=Window clips ( optional )
